  <p>“The mistake is investing 100-percent certainty in a result and not holding a probabilistic view of scientific truth or risk and benefit. When people are making decisions for their own well-being, they need to hold that uncertainty in mind.” 
<a href="https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/dont-believe-hype/">Catherine Kerr</a>.</p>

  <p>The same goes for investing 0-percent certainty in something.
<a href="https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/i-was-a-meditation-skeptic-until-i-tried-to-make-my-case/">Chadwick Matlin</a></p>
